{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477688"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14707"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14707"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.05,0.58,0.27,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7400"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115484"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7400"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97487"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5881"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18073"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115484"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department after a syncopal episode while playing basketball. His parent reports he suddenly collapsed without warning during a game. There was no seizure activity, and he regained consciousness within one minute. He has no previous episodes of syncope. His parent mentions that the boy\u0027s maternal uncle died suddenly at age 35 years while running. The boy has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 65/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals normal heart sounds with no murmurs. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG shows sinus rhythm with a heart rate of 65/min, PR interval 180 ms, QRS duration 90 ms, and QTc 435 ms (380-440).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and discharge home","Tilt table testing","Urgent cardiology review","24-hour Holter monitor","Electroencephalogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents several concerning features that suggest cardiac syncope rather than the more common vasovagal syncope. The syncope occurred during exercise, there was no prodrome, and there is a family history of sudden cardiac death at a young age. These are all red flag features that warrant urgent cardiac evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent cardiology review\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as this presentation could represent a life-threatening cardiac condition such as hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, long QT syndrome, or other inherited cardiac conditions. The cardiologist would likely arrange further investigations including echocardiogram, exercise stress testing, and possibly genetic testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour Holter monitor\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient as the initial investigation for suspected cardiac syncope. While it may be part of the cardiac workup, it should be arranged in conjunction with specialist review and other investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and discharge\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the high-risk features in this presentation. Cardiac causes of syncope, though less common than vasovagal syncope, carry significant mortality risk if undiagnosed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETilt table testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose vasovagal syncope, which typically occurs with prolonged standing or specific triggers and is preceded by prodromal symptoms such as lightheadedness, sweating, or nausea. These features are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectroencephalogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if seizure activity was observed or suspected. The description of sudden collapse with rapid recovery is more consistent with syncope than seizure, and the concerning features point toward a cardiac cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Family history of sudden cardiac death under 40 years of age is a red flag for cardiac syncope in children","Syncope during exercise is concerning for cardiac causes and requires urgent investigation","Vasovagal syncope typically has prodromal symptoms and occurs in upright position or with triggers"],"references":["Zavala R, Metais B, Tuckfield L, DelVecchio M, Aronoff S. Pediatric Syncope: A Systematic Review. Pediatr Emerg Care. 2020 Sep;36(9):442-445. doi: 10.1097/PEC.0000000000002149. PMID: 32530839; PMCID: PMC7469873.","C\u00f4t\u00e9 JM. Syncope in children and adolescents: Evaluation and treatment. Paediatr Child Health. 2001 Oct;6(8):549-51. doi: 10.1093/pch/6.8.549. PMID: 20084125; PMCID: PMC2805591."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97487"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14707"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97487"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T06:23:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T06:23:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7400"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115484"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"u